snippet.textDisplay:
I think I had a thought.

People are sleeping on Peacock and HBO MAX. I say this because these aren't the only services offered by their respective parent companies.

Peacock is a service for content owned by NBCUniversal, and who owns NBCUniversal? Comcast.

HBO MAX is a service for content owned by Warner Brothers, which is in turn owned by AT&T.

I know we joke about the increasing irrelevance of pay TV ("Wait, you still have cable? LOL, next you're going to tell me you still have a landline!") but Comcast has over 20 Million TV subscribers, and AT&T has 19.5 Million. And this isn't even getting into the internet subscriptions that would be needed to access the streaming services (28.6 Million for Comcast and 15.7 Million for AT&T, although given the industry's propensity to bundle services, there's likely a huge overlap between TV and Internet subscribers.)

And given the... shall we say "lax" regulatory environment surrounding telecommunications at the moment, I don't think anyone would file antitrust charges if these major telecom companies HAPPENED to make their hot new streaming services free for subscribers.
snippet.textOriginal:

People are sleeping on Peacock and HBO MAX. I say this because these aren't the only services offered by their respective parent companies. 

Peacock is a service for content owned by NBCUniversal, and who owns NBCUniversal? *Comcast.*

HBO MAX is a service for content owned by Warner Brothers, which is in turn owned _by AT&T._

I know we joke about the increasing irrelevance of pay TV ("Wait, you still have cable? LOL, next you're going to tell me you still have a landline!") but Comcast has over 20 Million TV subscribers, and AT&T has 19.5 Million. And this isn't even getting into the internet subscriptions that would be needed to _access the streaming services_ (28.6 Million for Comcast and 15.7 Million for AT&T, although given the industry's propensity to bundle services, there's likely a huge overlap between TV and Internet subscribers.) 

And given the... shall we say "lax" regulatory environment surrounding telecommunications at the moment, I don't think anyone would file antitrust charges if these major telecom companies HAPPENED to make their hot new streaming services free for subscribers.
